name: Ragnar Trail Tahoe - CA
intro:
Get ready! Ragnar Trail Tahoe - CA presented by Salomon is happening July 21-22, 2017 in a remote pocket of the Sierra Nevada Mountain Range at Royal Gorge Cross Country Ski Resort – a destination that true locals know and rave about. Find your inner wild as you and 7 of your friends (or 3 of your crazier friends!) conquer three different pristine running trails. Run through old-growth pines, cross over streams, and test your limits along razorback ridge lines that overlook sweeping vistas and views of Lake Van Norden and the Ice Lakes. In your downtime, kick back and relax at Ragnar Village. Bond with new and old friends as you enjoy s’mores, music and billions of stars. Grab your friends and mark your calendar for an unforgettable adventure – we’ll see you in Tahoe!

Royal Gorge and the Truckee Donner Land Trust – Royal Gorge opened in the 1970’s and is America’s largest Nordic Ski Resort. In 2012 the property went into foreclosure and the nearly 6,000 acres was purchased by the Truckee Donner Land Trust so that it will be forever protected. This purchase is considered one of the most important conservation victories for the Sierra region in a generation. The Land Trust’s goal is to make the property as popular in summer as it is in the winter with trails for mountain bikers, hikers, and equestrians.

village:
Ragnar Village is the heart and soul of the Ragnar Trail Relay. Each trail loop begins and ends in the Ragnar Village. It is the start line, the finish line, and the exchange point. After each loop you will return to the support of your teammates and the adulation of the teams around you. Ragnar Village will be complete with:

  • S'mores, Coffee, and Hot Chocolate 
  • Yoga (bring your own mat)
  • Food sales: Friday lunch, Friday dinner (free for registered runners), Saturday breakfast and lunch
  • 1 Free Meal per participant (Friday night dinner) Pasta dinner (vegetarian) with salad roll, cookie, and lemonade or iced tea.
  • Beer Garden Sales: Friday 11:00 AM — 10:00 PM and Saturday 11:00 AM — 6:00 PM (bring your ID)
  • Games and giveaways
  • Ragnar Swag available at the Merch Tent
  • Running Documentary
  • Billions of stars

Training by Salomon

At Salomon our goal is to inspire runners to go beyond the pavement and enjoy greater freedom to run anywhere. We believe that with some tips and training almost anyone can become a trail runner and run the Ragnar Trail Relay. We are here to guide you on your training journey as you prepare to run the Ragnar Trail Relay.

Team in Training - Greater Sacramento Area

Team in Training (TNT) is the flagship fundraising program for The Leukemia & Lymphoma Society (LLS) and the only endurance sports training program for charity that raises money for blood cancer research. TNT and LLS are changing the landscape of blood cancer, not someday but today, making TNT the perfect way to fundraise.

For further information about Team in Training, please visit: http://www.teamintraining.org/sac

meta_description: Get ready! Ragnar Trail Relays presented by Salomon is happening July 22-23, 2016 in a remote pocket of the Sierra Nevada Mountain Range at Royal Gorge Cross Country Ski Resort, a destination that true locals know and rave about. Find your inner wild as you and 7 of your friends (or 3 of your crazier friends!) conquer three different pristine running trails.

legs.name: Green Loop - Palisade Peak Trail
legs.description: The Green Loop takes you on a jaunt through the forest on double-track logging roads. Your footfall will be padded by bark chips, the birds will be chirping, and there will be a slight breeze. You will be happy. This is one of those runs that you can zone out and let the trees do the talking…good thing is, they don’t say much. After a mile-and-an-half you jump on a fun single-track that twists and turns through the trees. Every once in a while you will get a glimpse through the trees at the ridgelines above, where the Yellow and Red Loops await. After mile two the Yellow Loop will join into the fun and just beyond that the Red Loop will too. This means you are almost home. Go ahead, turn on those afterburners.

legs.name: Yellow Loop - Summit Valley View Trail
legs.description: Don’t worry, you aren’t going to get lost, stuck in a blizzard, and…well, you know. Yellow Loop leaves Ragnar Village with the Red Loop on a mostly flat double-track but after half-a-mile, that will change. A left turn onto a single-track and the climb begins. The climb is short but it will get those quads burning and the payoff is worth the effort. Near mile one the trail crests a ridgeline with great views. Look left for a view of Lake Van Norden, right for a view of Ice Lakes, and straight ahead for this trail’s namesake, Donner Pass. Get the pictures out of the way and then get moving, because you can fly down the next two miles of flowing single-track fun. In this section you will cross the Red Loop twice, the first time the Red Loop runners are headed uphill, the second time they are headed down, probably with an awestruck smile plastered on their face. At mile three the Yellow Loop pops out of the trees and onto a dirt road that parallels the effluent creek from Ice Lakes. A right turn, over a bridge, and one more steep climb and then you can put the thing on autopilot. The next two miles are a coast back to Ragnar Village.

legs.name: Red Loop - Razorback Ridge Trail
legs.description: This could be our most favorite trail of the entire Ragnar Trail Series. Don’t mistake that for the easiest trail, because nothing worthwhile is easy, and this trail is definitely worthwhile. It starts out easy enough, running alongside with the Yellow Loop on double-track and then after half-a-mile continues ahead alone. Just after the one mile mark the trail takes a couple of left turns onto a great single-track which meanders through old growth pines covered in neon green moss. This section starts out pretty mellow and gets steeper and steeper until you crest the ridgeline. The view is absolutely breathtaking, that is, if you weren’t already out of breath from the climb up to 7,500’. The next mile of running could be the best run of your life. The trail dances along the ridgeline, all the while providing 360 degree views of the Sierras. But it isn’t all downhill from here, just yet. You still have one last steep climb that takes you just below Rowton Peak. Before you turn right to blast downhill off of the ridgeline, give it one last look, heck this is trail running, stop and take a picture, that fits with Leave No Trace, right? The next three miles will go quick, there is even about a mile of pavement in there. But your mind and soul will not soon forget the view from Razorback Ridge.
